# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pci-dss
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] A **card security code** (**CSC**; also known as **CVC**, **CVV**, or several other names) is a series of numbers that, in addition to the bank card number, is printed (but not embossed) on a credit or debit card.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The CSC is used as a security feature for card-not-present transactions, where a personal identification number (PIN) cannot be manually entered by the cardholder (as they would during point-of-sale or card present transactions).
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] It was instituted to reduce the incidence of credit card fraud.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Unlike the card number, the CSC is deliberately not embossed, so that it is not read when using a mechanical credit card imprinter which will only pick up embossed numbers.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] These codes are in slightly different places for different card issuers.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The CSC for Visa, Mastercard, and Discover credit cards is a three-digit number on the back of the card, to the right of the signature box.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The CSC for American Express is a four-digit code on the front of the card above the account number.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] See the figures to the right for examples.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] CSC was originally developed in the UK as an eleven-character alphanumeric code by Equifax employee Michael Stone in 1995.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] After testing with the Littlewoods Home Shopping group and NatWest bank, the concept was adopted by the UK Association for Payment Clearing Services (APACS) and streamlined to the three-digit code known today.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Mastercard started issuing CVC2 numbers in 1997 and Visa in the United States issued them by 2001.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] American Express started to use the CSC in 1999, in response to growing Internet transactions and card member complaints of spending interruptions when the security of a card has been brought into question.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The card security code is typically the last three or four digits printed, not embossed like the card number, on the signature strip on the back of the card.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] On American Express cards, however, the card security code is the four digits printed (not embossed) on the front towards the right.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The card security code is not encoded on the magnetic stripe but is printed flat.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The CSC for each card (form 1 and 2) is generated by the card issuer when the card is issued.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] It is calculated by encrypting the bank card number and expiration date (two fields printed on the card) with encryption keys known only to the card issuer, and decimalising the result (in a similar manner to a hash function).
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] As a security measure, merchants who require the CVV2 for card-not-present transactions are required by the card issuer not to store the CVV2 once the individual transaction is authorized.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] This way, if a database of transactions is compromised, the CVV2 is not present and the stolen card numbers are less useful.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Virtual terminals and payment gateways do not store the CVV2 code; therefore, employees and customer service representatives with access to these web-based payment interfaces, who otherwise have access to complete card numbers, expiration dates, and other information, still lack the CVV2 code.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) also prohibits the storage of CSC (and other sensitive authorisation data) post transaction authorisation.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] This applies globally to anyone who stores, processes or transmits cardholder data.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Since the CSC is not contained on the magnetic stripe of the card, it is not typically included in the transaction when the card is used face to face at a merchant.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] However, some merchants in North America, such as Sears and Staples, require the code.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] For American Express cards, this has been an invariable practice (for card-not-present transactions) in European Union (EU) countries like Ireland and the United Kingdom since the start of 2005.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] This provides a level of protection to the bank/cardholder, in that a fraudulent merchant or employee cannot simply capture the magnetic stripe details of a card and use them later for card-not-present transactions over the phone, mail order or Internet.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] To do this, a merchant or its employee would also have to note the CVV2 visually and record it, which is more likely to arouse the cardholder's suspicion.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Supplying the CSC code in a transaction is intended to verify that the customer has the card in their possession.
[src:pci-dss/card-security-code] Knowledge of the code proves that the customer has seen the card, or has seen a record made by somebody who saw the card.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The main reason to mask data is to protect information that is classified as personally identifiable information, or mission critical data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] However, the data must remain usable for the purposes of undertaking valid test cycles.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It must also look real and appear consistent.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is more common to have masking applied to data that is represented outside of a corporate production system.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In other words, where data is needed for the purpose of application development, building program extensions and conducting various test cycles.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is common practice in enterprise computing to take data from the production systems to fill the data component, required for these non-production environments.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] However, this practice is not always restricted to non-production environments.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In some organizations, data that appears on terminal screens to call center operators may have masking dynamically applied based on user security permissions (e.g. preventing call center operators from viewing credit card numbers in billing systems).
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The primary concern from a corporate governance perspective is that personnel conducting work in these non-production environments are not always security cleared to operate with the information contained in the production data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This practice represents a security hole where data can be copied by unauthorized personnel, and security measures associated with standard production level controls can be easily bypassed.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This represents an access point for a data security breach.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The data must undergo enough changes so that it is not obvious that the masked data is from a source of production data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] For example, it may be common knowledge in an organisation that there are 10 senior managers all earning in excess of $300k.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] If a test environment of the organisation's HR System also includes 10 identities in the same earning-bracket, then other information could be pieced together to reverse-engineer a real-life identity.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Theoretically, if the data is obviously masked or obfuscated, then it would be reasonable for someone intending a data breach to assume that they could reverse engineer identity-data if they had some degree of knowledge of the identities in the production data-set.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Accordingly, data obfuscation or masking of a data-set applies in such a manner as to ensure that identity and sensitive data records are protected - not just the individual data elements in discrete fields and tables.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The masked values may be required to be consistent across multiple databases within an organization when the databases each contain the specific data element being masked.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Additional constraints as mentioned in (1) above may also apply depending on the data element(s) involved.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Where different character sets are used across the databases that need to connect in this scenario, a scheme of converting the original values to a common representation will need to be applied, either by the masking algorithm itself or prior to invoking said algorithm.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Substitution is one of the most effective methods of applying data masking and being able to preserve the authentic look and feel of the data records.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It allows the masking to be performed in such a manner that another authentic-looking value can be substituted for the existing value.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] There are several data field types where this approach provides optimal benefit in disguising the overall data subset as to whether or not it is a masked data set.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] For example, if dealing with source data which contains customer records, real life surname or first name can be randomly substituted from a supplied or customised look up file.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In most cases, the substitution files will need to be fairly extensive so having large substitution datasets as well the ability to apply customized data substitution sets should be a key element of the evaluation criteria for any data masking solution.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The shuffling method is a very common form of data obfuscation.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is similar to the substitution method but it derives the substitution set from the same column of data that is being masked.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In very simple terms, the data is randomly shuffled within the column.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] However, if used in isolation, anyone with any knowledge of the original data can then apply a "what if" scenario to the data set and then piece back together a real identity.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The shuffling method is also open to being reversed if the shuffling algorithm can be deciphered.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Data shuffling overcomes reservations about using perturbed or modified confidential data because it retains all the desirable properties of perturbation while performing better than other masking techniques in both data utility and disclosure risk.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Shuffling, however, has some real strengths in certain areas.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] If for instance, the end of year figures for financial information in a test data base, one can mask the names of the suppliers and then shuffle the value of the accounts throughout the masked database.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is highly unlikely that anyone, even someone with intimate knowledge of the original data could derive a true data record back to its original values.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The numeric variance method is very useful for applying to financial and date driven information fields.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Effectively, a method utilising this manner of masking can still leave a meaningful range in a financial data set such as payroll.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] If the variance applied is around +/- 10% then it is still a very meaningful data set in terms of the ranges of salaries that are paid to the recipients.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The same also applies to the date information.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Encryption is often the most complex approach to solving the data masking problem.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The encryption algorithm often requires that a "key" be applied to view the data based on user rights.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This often sounds like the best solution, but in practice the key may then be given out to personnel without the proper rights to view the data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This then defeats the purpose of the masking exercise.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Old databases may then get copied with the original credentials of the supplied key and the same uncontrolled problem lives on.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Recently, the problem of encrypting data while preserving the properties of the entities got recognition and a newly acquired interest among the vendors and academia.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] New challenge gave birth to algorithms performing format-preserving encryption.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] These are based on the accepted Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithmic mode recognized by NIST.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Sometimes a very simplistic approach to masking is adopted through applying a null value to a particular field.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The null value approach is really only useful to prevent visibility of the data element.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In almost all cases, it lessens the degree of data integrity that is maintained in the masked data set.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is not a realistic value and will then fail any application logic validation that may have been applied in the front end software that is in the system under test.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It also highlights to anyone that wishes to reverse engineer any of the identity data that data masking has been applied to some degree on the data set.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Character scrambling or masking out of certain fields is also another simplistic yet very effective method of preventing sensitive information to be viewed.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is really an extension of the previous method of nulling out, but there is a greater emphasis on keeping the data real and not fully masked all together.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This is commonly applied to credit card data in production systems.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] For instance, an operator at a call centre might bill an item to a customer's credit card.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] They then quote a billing reference to the card with the last 4 digits of XXXX XXXX xxxx 6789.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] As an operator they can only see the last 4 digits of the card number, but once the billing system passes the customer's details for charging, the full number is revealed to the payment gateway systems.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This system is not very effective for test systems, but it is very useful for the billing scenario detailed above.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] It is also commonly known as a dynamic data masking method.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Additional rules can also be factored into any masking solution regardless of how the masking methods are constructed.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Product agnostic white papers are a good source of information for exploring some of the more common complex requirements for enterprise masking solutions, which include row internal synchronization rules, table internal synchronization rules and table to Table Synchronization Rules.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Data masking is tightly coupled with building test data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Two major types of data masking are static and on-the-fly data masking.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Static data masking is usually performed on the golden copy of the database, but can also be applied to values in other sources, including files.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Deterministic masking is the process of replacing a value in a column with the same value whether in the same row, the same table, the same database/schema and between instances/servers/database types.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Example: A database has multiple tables, each with a column that has first names.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] With deterministic masking the first name will always be replaced with the same value – “Lynne” will always become “Denise” – wherever “Lynne” may be in the database.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] There are also alternatives to the static data masking that rely on stochastic perturbations of the data that preserve some of the statistical properties of the original data.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Examples of statistical data obfuscation methods include differential privacy and the *DataSifter* method.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] On-the-fly data masking happens in the process of transferring data from environment to environment without data touching the disk on its way.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The same technique is applied to "Dynamic Data Masking" but one record at a time.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This type of data masking is most useful for environments that do continuous deployments as well as for heavily integrated applications.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Organizations that employ continuous deployment or continuous delivery practices do not have the time necessary to create a backup and load it to the golden copy of the database.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Thus, continuously sending smaller subsets (deltas) of masked testing data from production is important.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In heavily integrated applications, developers get feeds from other production systems at the very onset of development and masking of these feeds is either overlooked and not budgeted until later, making organizations non-compliant.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Having on-the-fly data masking in place becomes essential.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is similar to on-the-fly data masking, but it differs in the sense that on-the-fly data masking is about copying data from one source to another source so that the latter can be shared.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic data masking happens at runtime, dynamically, and on-demand so that there doesn't need to be a second data source where to store the masked data dynamically.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic data masking enables several scenarios, many of which revolve around strict privacy regulations e.g. the Singapore Monetary Authority or the Privacy regulations in Europe.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is attribute-based and policy-driven.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic data masking can also be used to encrypt or decrypt values on the fly especially when using format-preserving encryption.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Several standards have emerged in recent years to implement dynamic data filtering and masking.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] For instance, XACML policies can be used to mask data inside databases.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Network proxy between the application and the database: Captures the SQL and applies rewrite on the select request.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Database proxy: is a variation of network proxy.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Database proxy is deployed usually between applications/users and the database.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Applications and users are connecting to the database through database security proxy.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] There are no changes to the way applications and users are connecting to the database.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] There is also no need of an agent to be installed on the database server.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The sql queries are rewritten, but when implemented, this type of dynamic data masking also supported within store procedures and database functions.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Network proxy between the end-user and the application: identifying text strings and replacing them.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This method is not applicable for complex applications as it will easily cause corruption when the real-time string replacement is unintentionally applied.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Code changes in the applications & XACML: code changes are usually hard to perform, impossible to maintain and not applicable for packaged applications.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Within the application run-time: By instrumenting the application run-time, policies are defined to rewrite the result set returned from the data sources, while having full visibility to the application user.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This method is the only applicable way to dynamically mask complex applications as it enables control to the data request, data result and user result.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Supported by a browser plugin: In the case of SaaS or local web applications, browser add-ons can be configured to mask data fields corresponding to precise CSS Selectors.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] This can either be accomplished by marking sensitive fields in the application, for example by a HTML class or by finding the right selectors that identify the fields to be obfuscated or masked.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] In latest years, organizations develop their new applications in the cloud more and more often, regardless of whether final applications will be hosted in the cloud or on- premises.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] The cloud solutions as of now allow organizations to use infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and software as a service.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] There are various modes of creating test data and moving it from on-premises databases to the cloud, or between different environments within the cloud.
[src:pci-dss/data-masking] Dynamic Data Masking becomes even more critical in cloud when customers need to protecting PII data while relying on cloud providers to administer their databases.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In cryptography, **encryption** (more specifically, encoding) is the process of transforming information in a way that, ideally, only authorized parties can decode.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This process converts the original representation of the information, known as plaintext, into an alternative form known as ciphertext.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Despite its goal, encryption does not itself prevent interference but denies the intelligible content to a would-be interceptor.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For technical reasons, an encryption scheme usually uses a pseudo-random encryption key generated by an algorithm.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] It is possible to decrypt the message without possessing the key but, for a well-designed encryption scheme, considerable computational resources and skills are required.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] An authorized recipient can easily decrypt the message with the key provided by the originator to recipients but not to unauthorized users.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Historically, various forms of encryption have been used to aid in cryptography.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Early encryption techniques were often used in military messaging.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Since then, new techniques have emerged and become commonplace in all areas of modern computing.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Modern encryption schemes use the concepts of public-key and symmetric-key.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Modern encryption techniques ensure security because modern computers are inefficient at cracking the encryption.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] One of the earliest forms of encryption is symbol replacement, which was first found in the tomb of Khnumhotep II, who lived in 1900 BC Egypt.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Symbol replacement encryption is "non-standard," which means that the symbols require a cipher or key to understand.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This type of early encryption was used throughout Ancient Greece and Rome for military purposes.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] One of the most famous military encryption developments was the Caesar cipher, in which a plaintext letter is shifted a fixed number of positions along the alphabet to get the encoded letter.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] A message encoded with this type of encryption could be decoded with a fixed number on the Caesar cipher.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Around 800 AD, Arab mathematician al-Kindi developed the technique of frequency analysis – which was an attempt to crack ciphers systematically, including the Caesar cipher.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This technique looked at the frequency of letters in the encrypted message to determine the appropriate shift: for example, the most common letter in English text is E and is therefore likely to be represented by the letter that appears most commonly in the ciphertext.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This technique was rendered ineffective by the polyalphabetic cipher, described by al-Qalqashandi (1355–1418) and Leon Battista Alberti (in 1465), which varied the substitution alphabet as encryption proceeded in order to confound such analysis.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Around 1790, Thomas Jefferson theorized a cipher to encode and decode messages to provide a more secure way of military correspondence.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The cipher, known today as the Wheel Cipher or the Jefferson Disk, although never actually built, was theorized as a spool that could jumble an English message up to 36 characters.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The message could be decrypted by plugging in the jumbled message to a receiver with an identical cipher.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] A similar device to the Jefferson Disk, the M-94, was developed in 1917 independently by US Army Major Joseph Mauborne.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This device was used in U.S. military communications until 1942.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In World War II, the Axis powers used a more advanced version of the M-94 called the Enigma Machine.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The Enigma Machine was more complex because unlike the Jefferson Wheel and the M-94, each day the jumble of letters switched to a completely new combination.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Each day's combination was only known by the Axis, so many thought the only way to break the code would be to try over 17,000 combinations within 24 hours.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The Allies used computing power to severely limit the number of reasonable combinations they needed to check every day, leading to the breaking of the Enigma Machine.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Today, encryption is used in the transfer of communication over the Internet for security and commerce.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] As computing power continues to increase, computer encryption is constantly evolving to prevent eavesdropping attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] One of the first "modern" cipher suites, DES, used a 56-bit key with 72,057,594,037,927,936 possibilities; it was cracked in 1999 by EFF's brute-force DES cracker, which required 22 hours and 15 minutes to do so.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Modern encryption standards often use stronger key sizes, such as AES (256-bit mode), TwoFish, ChaCha20-Poly1305, Serpent (configurable up to 512-bit).
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Cipher suites that use a 128-bit or higher key, like AES, cannot be brute-forced because the total number of keys is 3.4028237e+38 possibilities.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The most likely option for cracking ciphers with large key sizes is to find vulnerabilities in the cipher itself, like inherent biases and backdoors or by exploiting physical side effects through Side-channel attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For example, RC4, a stream cipher, was cracked due to inherent biases and vulnerabilities in the cipher.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In the context of cryptography, encryption serves as a mechanism to ensure confidentiality.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Since data may be visible on the Internet, sensitive information such as passwords and personal communication may be exposed to potential interceptors.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The process of encrypting and decrypting messages involves keys.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The two main types of keys in cryptographic systems are symmetric-key and public-key (also known as asymmetric-key).
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Many complex cryptographic algorithms often use simple modular arithmetic in their implementations.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In symmetric-key schemes, the encryption and decryption keys are the same.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Communicating parties must have the same key in order to achieve secure communication.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The German Enigma Machine used a new symmetric-key each day for encoding and decoding messages.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In public-key cryptography schemes, the encryption key is published for anyone to use and encrypt messages.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] However, only the receiving party has access to the decryption key that enables messages to be read.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Public-key encryption was first described in a secret document in 1973; beforehand, all encryption schemes were symmetric-key (also called private-key).
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Although published subsequently, the work of Diffie and Hellman was published in a journal with a large readership, and the value of the methodology was explicitly described.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The method became known as the Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] RSA (Rivest–Shamir–Adleman) is another notable public-key cryptosystem.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Created in 1978, it is still used today for applications involving digital signatures.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Using number theory, the RSA algorithm selects two prime numbers, which help generate both the encryption and decryption keys.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] A publicly available public-key encryption application called Pretty Good Privacy (PGP) was written in 1991 by Phil Zimmermann, and distributed free of charge with source code.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] PGP was purchased by Symantec in 2010 and is regularly updated.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption has long been used by militaries and governments to facilitate secret communication.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] It is now commonly used in protecting information within many kinds of civilian systems.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For example, the Computer Security Institute reported that in 2007, 71% of companies surveyed used encryption for some of their data in transit, and 53% used encryption for some of their data in storage.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption can be used to protect data "at rest", such as information stored on computers and storage devices (e.g.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In recent years, there have been numerous reports of confidential data, such as customers' personal records, being exposed through loss or theft of laptops or backup drives; encrypting such files at rest helps protect them if physical security measures fail.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Digital rights management systems, which prevent unauthorized use or reproduction of copyrighted material and protect software against reverse engineering (see also copy protection), is another somewhat different example of using encryption on data at rest.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption is also used to protect data in transit, for example data being transferred via networks (e.g. the Internet, e-commerce), mobile telephones, wireless microphones, wireless intercom systems, Bluetooth devices and bank automatic teller machines.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] There have been numerous reports of data in transit being intercepted in recent years.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Data should also be encrypted when transmitted across networks in order to protect against eavesdropping of network traffic by unauthorized users.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption plays a central role in meeting regulatory requirements for the protection of sensitive data.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Under the HIPAA Security Rule, encryption of electronic protected health information (ePHI) is classified as an "addressable" implementation specification, meaning covered entities must implement it or document why an equivalent alternative measure is reasonable and appropriate.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Notably, the HIPAA Breach Notification Rule provides a safe harbor for encrypted data: breaches involving ePHI that has been encrypted in accordance with NIST standards are not considered reportable breaches.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] A proposed update to the HIPAA Security Rule (NPRM, December 2024) would make encryption of ePHI at rest and in transit a mandatory requirement, removing its current "addressable" status.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) requires encryption of cardholder data both in storage (Requirement 3) and during transmission over open public networks (Requirement 4), specifying the use of strong cryptographic algorithms.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Conventional methods for permanently deleting data from a storage device involve overwriting the device's whole content with zeros, ones, or other patterns – a process which can take a significant amount of time, depending on the capacity and the type of storage medium.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Cryptography offers a way of making the erasure almost instantaneous.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] An example implementation of this method can be found on iOS devices, where the cryptographic key is kept in a dedicated 'effaceable storage'.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Because the key is stored on the same device, this setup on its own does not offer full privacy or security protection if an unauthorized person gains physical access to the device.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption is used in the 21st century to protect digital data and information systems.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] As computing power increased over the years, encryption technology has only become more advanced and secure.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] However, this advancement in technology has also exposed a potential limitation of today's encryption methods.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The length of the encryption key is an indicator of the strength of the encryption method.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For example, the original encryption key, DES (Data Encryption Standard), was 56 bits, meaning it had 2^56 combination possibilities.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] With today's computing power, a 56-bit key is no longer secure, being vulnerable to brute force attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Quantum computing uses properties of quantum mechanics in order to process large amounts of data simultaneously.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Quantum computing has been found to achieve computing speeds thousands of times faster than today's supercomputers.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This computing power presents a challenge to today's encryption technology.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For example, RSA encryption uses the multiplication of very large prime numbers to create a semiprime number for its public key.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Decoding this key without its private key requires this semiprime number to be factored, which can take a very long time to do with modern computers.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] It would take a supercomputer anywhere between weeks to months to factor in this key.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] However, quantum computing can use quantum algorithms to factor this semiprime number in the same amount of time it takes for normal computers to generate it.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This would make all data protected by current public-key encryption vulnerable to quantum computing attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Other encryption techniques like elliptic curve cryptography and symmetric key encryption are also vulnerable to quantum computing.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] While quantum computing could be a threat to encryption security in the future, quantum computing as it currently stands is still very limited.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Quantum computing currently is not commercially available, cannot handle large amounts of code, and only exists as computational devices, not computers.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Furthermore, quantum computing advancements will be able to be used in favor of encryption as well.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The National Security Agency (NSA) is currently preparing post-quantum encryption standards for the future.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Quantum encryption promises a level of security that will be able to counter the threat of quantum computing.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encryption is an important tool but is not sufficient alone to ensure the security or privacy of sensitive information throughout its lifetime.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Most applications of encryption protect information only at rest or in transit, leaving sensitive data in clear text and potentially vulnerable to improper disclosure during processing, such as by a cloud service for example.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Homomorphic encryption and secure multi-party computation are emerging techniques to compute encrypted data; these techniques are general and Turing complete but incur high computational and/or communication costs.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] In response to encryption of data at rest, cyber-adversaries have developed new types of attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] These more recent threats to encryption of data at rest include cryptographic attacks, stolen ciphertext attacks, attacks on encryption keys, insider attacks, data corruption or integrity attacks, data destruction attacks, and ransomware attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Data fragmentation and active defense data protection technologies attempt to counter some of these attacks, by distributing, moving, or mutating ciphertext so it is more difficult to identify, steal, corrupt, or destroy.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The question of balancing the need for national security with the right to privacy has been debated for years, since encryption has become critical in today's digital society.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The modern encryption debate started around the '90s when US government tried to ban cryptography because, according to them, it would threaten national security.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The debate is polarized around two opposing views.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Those who see strong encryption as a problem making it easier for criminals to hide their illegal acts online and others who argue that encryption keep digital communications safe.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The debate heated up in 2014, when Big Tech like Apple and Google set encryption by default in their devices.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] This was the start of a series of controversies that puts governments, companies and internet users at stake.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Authenticated encryption algorithms are designed to provide both encryption and integrity protection together.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Standards for cryptographic software and hardware to perform encryption are widely available, but successfully using encryption to ensure security may be a challenging problem.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] A single error in system design or execution can allow successful attacks.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Sometimes an adversary can obtain unencrypted information without directly undoing the encryption.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] See for example traffic analysis, TEMPEST, or Trojan horse.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encrypting at the time of creation is only secure if the encryption device itself has correct keys and has not been tampered with.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] If an endpoint device has been configured to trust a root certificate that an attacker controls, for example, then the attacker can both inspect and tamper with encrypted data by performing a man-in-the-middle attack anywhere along the message's path.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] The common practice of TLS interception by network operators represents a controlled and institutionally sanctioned form of such an attack, but countries have also attempted to employ such attacks as a form of control and censorship.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Even when encryption effectively conceals a message’s content and prevents tampering, the *length* of the ciphertext remains a form of metadata that can leak sensitive information.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] For instance, the well-known CRIME and BREACH attacks against HTTPS exploited information leakage through encrypted message length as a side-channel attack.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Traffic analysis more broadly refers to techniques that use metadata—such as message size and timing—to infer information about communication patterns.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Applying padding to a message before encryption can help obscure its true plaintext length, though this increases the ciphertext size and adds bandwidth overhead.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Padding may be applied randomly or deterministically, each approach involving different trade-offs.
[src:pci-dss/encryption] Encrypting and padding data to produce padded uniform random blobs (PURBs) ensures that the ciphertext reveals no metadata about the plaintext’s structure, leaking only asymptotically minimal $O(\log \log M)$ information through its length.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The **Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard** (**PCI DSS**) is a global data security standard that regulates how entities store, process, and transmit cardholder data (CHD) and/or sensitive authentication data (SAD).
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS includes guidelines regarding components of organizations' technical and operational system that are related to such data.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Cardholder Data refers to information including Primary Account Numbers (PAN), cardholder names, expiration dates, and service codes.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Sensitive authentication data refers to information including "full track data (magnetic-stripe data or equivalent on a chip)," card verification codes, and PINs/PIN blocks.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] This standard is administered by the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council, and its use is enforced by the major payment card brands.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS was created to improve and streamline the security controls organizations use when handling cardholder data and reduce credit card fraud.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These organizations, including merchants and service providers, must prove compliance to the PCI DSS through an assessment and validation process.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands issue fines and other penalties when merchants or service providers fail to prove compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Before the PCI DSS was launched, payment card information security was handled by the five major payment card brands: Visa, Mastercard, American Express, Discover, and JCB.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The intentions of each were roughly similar: to create an additional level of protection for card issuers by ensuring that merchants meet minimum levels of security when they handle payment cards and related account information.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As payment card fraud rose in the late 1990s and early 2000s, the major payment card brands felt a growing need to streamline and unify these information security standards.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each program had its own methods and guidance regarding compliance validation, assessments, and requirements.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To address interoperability problems among the existing standards, the combined effort by these payment card brands resulted in the release of version 1.0 of PCI DSS in December 2004.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The main payment card brands then founded the Payment Card Industry Security Standards Council (PCI SSC) and aligned their policies to create the PCI DSS.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS has since been implemented and followed by numerous organizations around the world.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] MasterCard, American Express, Visa, JCB International and Discover Financial Services established the PCI SSC in September 2006 as a global administrative and governing entity that mandates the evolution and development of the PCI DSS.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Independent private organizations can also participate in PCI development as part of the PCI Security Standards Council Participating Organization Program.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] To join that program, organizations must register as a PCI SSC Participating Organization (PO).
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each participating organization joins a SIG (Special Interest Group) and contributes to activities mandated by the group.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS is a living document that is regularly updated by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI SSC releases major version updates, such as version 4.0, approximately every few years.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Minor updates, such as version 4.0.1, are released more frequently and typically add small changes or clarifications.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] When updates are released, organizations have a transition period during which they must become familiar with the new changes and begin ensuring compliance with the current version.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] During the transition period, organizations are only required to be compliant with either the current version or the previous version.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each PCI DSS version has divided these six requirement groups differently, but the twelve requirements have not changed since the inception of the standard.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Testing: The processes and methodologies carried out by the assessor for the confirmation of proper implementation.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Guidance: Explains the purpose of the requirement and the corresponding content, which can assist in its proper definition.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Apply secure configurations to all system components.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect cardholder data with strong cryptography during transmission over open, public networks.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Protect all systems and networks from malicious software.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Develop and maintain secure systems and software.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict access to system components and cardholder data by business need to know.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Identify users and authenticate access to system components.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Restrict physical access to cardholder data.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Log and monitor all access to system components and cardholder data.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Test security of systems and networks regularly.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Support information security with organizational policies and programs.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants that store, process, and transmit cardholder data are subject to PCI DSS standards, and thus, must be deemed PCI-compliant.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS framework classifies these entities into merchant levels that determine the type of reporting a business must complete to achieve compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A business' merchant level is determined by its dataset size which refers to the number of transactions a business makes annually.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An acquirer or payment brand may manually place an organization into a reporting level at its discretion.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Not all payment card brands use all four merchant levels, and each level's transaction volume can vary among payment card brands.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] For instance, Visa only has three merchant levels.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each card issuer maintains a table of compliance levels and a table for service providers.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to the PCI DSS, third-party service providers that store, process, or transmit cardholder data, or have access to customers’ account data are subject to PCI DSS standards.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers can include payment software vendors, software as a service (SaaS), data centers, and other such entities.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are required to prove PCI DSS compliance through the assessment process.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The type of reporting process a service provider must complete are dependent on the type of service provider.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Service providers are classified into levels which determine the reporting required for compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The payment card brands regularly require both merchants and service providers to demonstrate PCI DSS compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] PCI DSS compliance involves implementing security controls that follow all requirements of the PCI DSS and passing the PCI DSS assessment process to achieve compliance validation.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major credit card brands enforce PCI DSS compliance by issuing fines for merchants who do not obtain compliance validation.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants and service providers sign business-to-business contracts with payment processors and payment card brands, which outline such fines and fees.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In the event of a merchant's compliance violation, payment card brands issue fines to the acquiring bank who then fines or otherwise penalizes the non-compliant merchant.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Obtaining PCI DSS compliance and navigating the assessment process can be complicated, which is why many businesses often struggle with this.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Verizon's 2018 Payment Security Report, 47.5% of organizations were not PCI DSS compliant during interim compliance validation.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The number of organizations achieving compliance had been steadily increasing through the early 2010s, but this increase may likely have dropped in recent years.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation involves the evaluation and confirmation that the security controls and procedures have been implemented according to the PCI DSS.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Validation occurs through an annual assessment, either by an external entity, or by self-assessment.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Perform the PCI DSS assessment of the environment.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the applicable report for the assessment according to PCI DSS guidance and instructions.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Complete the Attestation of Compliance for Service Providers or Merchants, as applicable, in its entirety.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Submit the applicable PCI SSC documentation and the Attestation of Compliance, along with any other requested documentation to the requesting organization (those that manage compliance programs such as payment brands and acquirers (for merchants), or other requesters (for service providers)).
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Report on Compliance (ROC) is conducted by a PCI Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) and is intended to provide independent validation of an entity's compliance with the PCI DSS standard.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A completed ROC results in two documents: a ROC Reporting Template populated with detailed explanation of the testing completed, and an Attestation of Compliance (AOC) documenting that a ROC has been completed and the overall conclusion of the ROC.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI DSS Self-Assessment Questionnaire (SAQ) is a validation tool intended for small to medium sized merchants and service providers to assess their own PCI DSS compliance status.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] There are multiple types of SAQ, each with a different length depending on the entity type and payment model used.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Each SAQ question has a yes-or-no answer, and any "no" response requires the entity to indicate its future implementation.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] As with ROCs, an attestation of compliance (AOC) based on the SAQ is also completed.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The PCI Security Standards Council maintains a program to certify companies and individuals to perform assessment activities.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A Qualified Security Assessor (QSA) is an individual certified by the PCI Security Standards Council to validate another entity's PCI DSS compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] QSAs must be employed and sponsored by a QSA Company, which also must be certified by the PCI Security Standards Council.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] An Internal Security Assessor (ISA) is an individual who has earned a certificate from the PCI Security Standards Council for their sponsoring organization, and can conduct PCI self-assessments for their organization.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The ISA program was designed to help Level 2 merchants meet Mastercard compliance validation requirements.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISA certification empowers an individual to conduct an appraisal of his or her association and propose security solutions and controls for PCI DSS compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] ISAs are in charge of cooperation and participation with QSAs.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Although the PCI DSS must be implemented by all entities which process, store or transmit cardholder data and/or sensitive authentication data or could impact the security of such information, formal validation of PCI DSS compliance is not mandatory for all entities.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Visa and Mastercard require merchants and service providers to be validated according to the PCI DSS; Visa also offers a Technology Innovation Program (TIP), an alternative program which allows qualified merchants to discontinue the annual PCI DSS validation assessment.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Merchants are eligible if they take alternative precautions against fraud, such as the use of EMV or point-to-point encryption.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Issuing banks are not required to undergo PCI DSS validation, although they must secure sensitive data in a PCI DSS-compliant manner.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Acquiring banks must comply with PCI DSS and have their compliance validated with an audit.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In a security breach, any compromised entity which was not PCI DSS-compliant at the time of the breach may be subject to additional penalties (such as fines) from card brands or acquiring banks.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] No governing body/agency requires or enforces PCI DSS compliance, but if any PCI DSS requirements conflict with country, state, or local law, the law will apply.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The European Union’s (EU) General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is a legislative standard governing personal data.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] GDPR has similar security control standards as PCI DSS in regards to cardholder data because cardholder data is considered a form of personal data under GDPR.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Hence, for many European organizations, a PCI DSS breach often constitutes a GDPR breach as well, which can result in fines from both major payment card brands and the European Union.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] These GDPR fines can be up to "€20 million or 4% of annual global turnover" (whichever is greatest).
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] While compliance with PCI DSS is not required by federal law in the United States, the laws of some US states refer to PCI DSS directly or make equivalent provisions.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2007, Minnesota enacted a law prohibiting the retention of some types of payment-card data more than 48 hours after authorization of a transaction.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Nevada incorporated the standard into state law two years later, requiring compliance by merchants doing business in that state with the current PCI DSS and shielding compliant entities from liability.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The Nevada law also allows merchants to avoid liability by other approved security standards.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In 2010, Washington also incorporated the standard into state law.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Unlike Nevada's law, entities are not required to be PCI DSS-compliant; however, compliant entities are shielded from liability in the event of a data breach.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Legal scholars Edward Morse and Vasant Raval have said that by enshrining PCI DSS compliance in legislation, card networks reallocated the cost of fraud from card issuers to merchants.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] The major payment card brands impose fines for non-compliance.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Some business owners, small business owners especially, criticize the PCI DSS system because the payment card brands impose fines on businesses even if no fraud occurs.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Stephen and Theodora "Cissy" McComb, owners of a small restaurant called Cisero's Ristorante and Nightclub in Park City, Utah, were fined for a breach for which two forensics firms could not find evidence.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] They claim the PCI DSS system exists primarily for major card brands to extract profit from these merchant companies rather than ensure cardholder data security.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Proponents of the PCI DSS maintain that the PCI DSS may compel businesses to pay more attention to IT security, even if minimum standards are not enough to eradicate security problems.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Former Visa chief enterprise risk officer Ellen Richey said in 2018, "No compromised entity has yet been found to be in compliance with PCI DSS at the time of a breach".
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] However, a 2008 breach of Heartland Payment Systems (validated as PCI DSS-compliant) resulted in the compromising of more than one hundred million card numbers.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Around that time, Hannaford Brothers and TJX Companies (also validated as PCI DSS-compliant) were similarly breached as a result of the allegedly-coordinated efforts of Albert Gonzalez and two unnamed Russian hackers.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] In December 2013, more than forty million Target customer accounts were compromised in a data breach.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Target’s Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer at the time John Mulligan confirmed that Target was certified PCI compliant months before the breach in September 2013.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] News of incidents was widespread and called into question the adequacy of the PCI DSS.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Assessments examine the compliance of merchants and service providers with the PCI DSS at a specific point in time, frequently using sampling to allow compliance to be demonstrated with representative systems and processes.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] It is the responsibility of the merchant and service provider to achieve, demonstrate, and maintain compliance throughout the annual validation-and-assessment cycle across all systems and processes.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] A breakdown in merchant and service-provider compliance with the written standard may have been responsible for the breaches; Hannaford Brothers received its PCI DSS compliance validation one day after it had been made aware of a two-month-long compromise of its internal systems.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Compliance validation is required only for level 1 to 3 merchants and may be optional for Level 4, depending on the card brand and acquirer.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] According to Visa's compliance validation details for merchants, level-4 merchant compliance-validation requirements ("Merchants processing less than 20,000 Visa e-commerce transactions annually and all other merchants processing up to 1 million Visa transactions annually") are set by the acquirer.
[src:pci-dss/payment-card-industry-data-security-standard] Over 80 percent of payment-card compromises between 2005 and 2007 affected level-4 merchants, who handled 32 percent of all such transactions.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:pci-dss/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system must be secured and validated using security best practices applicable to sensitive data protection, secure storage, audit, authentication and authorization.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization system provides data processing applications with the authority and interfaces to request tokens, or detokenize back to sensitive data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The security and risk reduction benefits of tokenization require that the tokenization system is logically isolated and segmented from data processing systems and applications that previously processed or stored sensitive data replaced by tokens.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Only the tokenization system can tokenize data to create tokens, or detokenize back to redeem sensitive data under strict security controls.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The token generation method must be proven to have the property that there is no feasible means through direct attack, cryptanalysis, side channel analysis, token mapping table exposure or brute force techniques to reverse tokens back to live data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Replacing live data with tokens in systems is intended to minimize exposure of sensitive data to those applications, stores, people and processes, reducing risk of compromise or accidental exposure and unauthorized access to sensitive data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Applications can operate using tokens instead of live data, with the exception of a small number of trusted applications explicitly permitted to detokenize when strictly necessary for an approved business purpose.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems may be operated in-house within a secure isolated segment of the data center, or as a service from a secure service provider.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization may be used to safeguard sensitive data involving, for example, bank accounts, financial statements, medical records, criminal records, driver's licenses, loan applications, stock trades, voter registrations, and other types of personally identifiable information (PII).
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is often used in credit card processing.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council defines tokenization as "a process by which the primary account number (PAN) is replaced with a surrogate value called a token.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] A PAN may be linked to a reference number through the tokenization process.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In this case, the merchant simply has to retain the token and a reliable third party controls the relationship and holds the PAN.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The token may be created independently of the PAN, or the PAN can be used as part of the data input to the tokenization technique.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The communication between the merchant and the third-party supplier must be secure to prevent an attacker from intercepting to gain the PAN and the token.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] De-tokenization is the reverse process of redeeming a token for its associated PAN value.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The security of an individual token relies predominantly on the infeasibility of determining the original PAN knowing only the surrogate value".
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The choice of tokenization as an alternative to other techniques such as encryption will depend on varying regulatory requirements, interpretation, and acceptance by respective auditing or assessment entities.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This is in addition to any technical, architectural or operational constraint that tokenization imposes in practical use.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The concept of tokenization, as adopted by the industry today, has existed since the first currency systems emerged centuries ago as a means to reduce risk in handling high value financial instruments by replacing them with surrogate equivalents.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In the physical world, coin tokens have a long history of use replacing the financial instrument of minted coins and banknotes.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In more recent history, subway tokens and casino chips found adoption for their respective systems to replace physical currency and cash handling risks such as theft.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Exonumia and scrip are terms synonymous with such tokens.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In the digital world, similar substitution techniques have been used since the 1970s as a means to isolate real data elements from exposure to other data systems.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In databases for example, surrogate key values have been used since 1976 to isolate data associated with the internal mechanisms of databases and their external equivalents for a variety of uses in data processing.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] More recently, these concepts have been extended to consider this isolation tactic to provide a security mechanism for the purposes of data protection.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In the payment card industry, tokenization is one means of protecting sensitive cardholder data in order to comply with industry standards and government regulations.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization was applied to payment card data by Shift4 Corporation and released to the public during an industry Security Summit in Las Vegas, Nevada in 2005.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The technology is meant to prevent the theft of the credit card information in storage.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Shift4 defines tokenization as: "The concept of using a non-decryptable piece of data to represent, by reference, sensitive or secret data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] To protect data over its full lifecycle, tokenization is often combined with end-to-end encryption to secure data in transit to the tokenization system or service, with a token replacing the original data on return.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] For example, to avoid the risks of malware stealing data from low-trust systems such as point of sale (POS) systems, as in the Target breach of 2013, cardholder data encryption must take place prior to card data entering the POS and not after.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also specified end-to-end encryption (certified point-to-point encryption—P2PE) for various service implementations in various PCI Council Point-to-point Encryption documents.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization systems share several components according to established standards.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Token mapping – this is the process of assigning the created token value to its original value.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] To enable permitted look-ups of the original value using the token as the index, a secure cross-reference database must be constructed.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Token data store – this is a central repository for the token mapping process that holds the original sensitive values and their related token values.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Sensitive data and token values must be securely kept in an encrypted format.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Strong key management procedures are required for sensitive data encryption on token data stores.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization and "classic" encryption effectively protect data if implemented properly, and a computer security system may use both.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] While similar in certain regards, tokenization and classic encryption differ in a few key aspects.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Both are cryptographic data security methods and they essentially have the same function, however they do so with differing processes and have different effects on the data they are protecting.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is a non-mathematical approach that replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive substitutes without altering the type or length of data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This is an important distinction from encryption because changes in data length and type can render information unreadable in intermediate systems such as databases.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenized data can still be processed by legacy systems which makes tokenization more flexible than classic encryption.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In many situations, the encryption process is a constant consumer of processing power, hence such a system needs significant expenditures in specialized hardware and software.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Another difference is that tokens require significantly less computational resources to process.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] With tokenization, specific data is kept fully or partially visible for processing and analytics while sensitive information is kept hidden.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This allows tokenized data to be processed more quickly and reduces the strain on system resources.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This can be a key advantage in systems that rely on high performance.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In comparison to encryption, tokenization technologies reduce time, expense, and administrative effort while enabling teamwork and communication.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] There are many ways that tokens can be classified.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] However, there is currently no unified classification.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be single or multi-use, cryptographic or non-cryptographic, reversible or irreversible, authenticable or non-authenticable, and various combinations thereof.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In the context of payments, the difference between high and low value tokens plays a significant role.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] High-value tokens (HVT) serve as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions and are used as an instrument for completing a payment transaction.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In order to function, they must look like actual PANs.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Multiple HVT can map back to a single PAN and a single physical credit card without the owner being aware of it.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Additionally, HVT can be limited to certain networks and/or merchants whereas PANs cannot.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] HVT can also be bound to specific devices so that anomalies between token use, physical devices, and geographic locations can be flagged as potentially fraudulent.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] HVT blocking enhances efficiency by reducing computational costs while maintaining accuracy and reducing record linkage as it reduces the number of records that are compared.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Low-value tokens (LVT) also act as surrogates for actual PANs in payment transactions, however they serve a different purpose.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] LVT cannot be used by themselves to complete a payment transaction.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In order for an LVT to function, it must be possible to match it back to the actual PAN it represents, albeit only in a tightly controlled fashion.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Using tokens to protect PANs becomes ineffectual if a tokenization system is breached, therefore securing the tokenization system itself is extremely important.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] First generation tokenization systems use a database to map from live data to surrogate substitute tokens and back.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This requires the storage, management, and continuous backup for every new transaction added to the token database to avoid data loss.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Another problem is ensuring consistency across data centers, requiring continuous synchronization of token databases.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Significant consistency, availability and performance trade-offs, per the CAP theorem, are unavoidable with this approach.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This overhead adds complexity to real-time transaction processing to avoid data loss and to assure data integrity across data centers, and also limits scale.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Storing all sensitive data in one service creates an attractive target for attack and compromise, and introduces privacy and legal risk in the aggregation of data Internet privacy, particularly in the EU.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Another limitation of tokenization technologies is measuring the level of security for a given solution through independent validation.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] With the lack of standards, the latter is critical to establish the strength of tokenization offered when tokens are used for regulatory compliance.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The method of generating tokens may also have limitations from a security perspective.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] With concerns about security and attacks to random number generators, which are a common choice for the generation of tokens and token mapping tables, scrutiny must be applied to ensure proven and validated methods are used versus arbitrary design.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Random-number generators have limitations in terms of speed, entropy, seeding and bias, and security properties must be carefully analysed and measured to avoid predictability and compromise.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Stateless tokenization allows live data elements to be mapped to surrogate values randomly, without relying on a database, while maintaining the isolation properties of tokenization.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] November 2014, American Express released its token service which meets the EMV tokenization standard.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Other notable examples of tokenization-based payment systems, according to the EMVCo standard, include Google Wallet, Apple Pay, Samsung Pay, Microsoft Wallet, Fitbit Pay and Garmin Pay.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Visa uses tokenization techniques to provide a secure online and mobile shopping.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Using blockchain, as opposed to relying on trusted third parties, it is possible to run highly accessible, tamper-resistant databases for transactions.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] With help of blockchain, tokenization is the process of converting the value of a tangible or intangible asset into a token that can be exchanged on the network.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This enables the tokenization of conventional financial assets, for instance, by transforming rights into a digital token backed by the asset itself using blockchain technology.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Besides that, tokenization enables the simple and efficient compartmentalization and management of data across multiple users.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Individual tokens created through tokenization can be used to split ownership and partially resell an asset.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Consequently, only entities with the appropriate token can access the data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Numerous blockchain companies support asset tokenization.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In 2019, eToro acquired Firmo and renamed as eToroX.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Through its Token Management Suite, which is backed by USD-pegged stablecoins, eToroX enables asset tokenization.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The tokenization of equity is facilitated by STOKR, a platform that links investors with small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokens issued through the STOKR platform are legally recognized as transferable securities under European Union capital market regulations.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Breakers enable tokenization of intellectual property, allowing content creators to issue their own digital tokens.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be distributed to a variety of project participants.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Without intermediaries or governing body, content creators can integrate reward-sharing features into the token.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Building an alternate payments system requires a number of entities working together in order to deliver near field communication (NFC) or other technology based payment services to the end users.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] One of the issues is the interoperability between the players and to resolve this issue the role of trusted service manager (TSM) is proposed to establish a technical link between mobile network operators (MNO) and providers of services, so that these entities can work together.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can play a role in mediating such services.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization as a security strategy lies in the ability to replace a real card number with a surrogate (target removal) and the subsequent limitations placed on the surrogate card number (risk reduction).
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] If the surrogate value can be used in an unlimited fashion or even in a broadly applicable manner, the token value gains as much value as the real credit card number.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In these cases, the token may be secured by a second dynamic token that is unique for each transaction and also associated to a specific payment card.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Example of dynamic, transaction-specific tokens include cryptograms used in the EMV (Europay, Mastercard, and Visa) specification.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, an industry-wide set of guidelines that must be met by any organization that stores, processes, or transmits cardholder data, mandates that credit card data must be protected when stored.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization, as applied to payment card data, is often implemented to meet this mandate, replacing credit card and automated clearing house (ACH) numbers in some systems with a random value or string of characters.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokens can be formatted in a variety of ways.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Some token service providers or tokenization products generate the surrogate values in such a way as to match the format of the original sensitive data.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In the case of payment card data, a token might be the same length as a primary account number (bank card number) and contain elements of the original data such as the last four digits of the card number.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] When a payment card authorization request is made to verify the legitimacy of a transaction, a token might be returned to the merchant instead of the card number, along with the authorization code for the transaction.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The token is stored in the receiving system while the actual cardholder data is mapped to the token in a secure tokenization system.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Storage of tokens and payment card data must comply with current PCI standards, including the use of strong cryptography.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization is currently in standards definition in ANSI X9 as X9.119 Part 2.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] X9 is responsible for the industry standards for financial cryptography and data protection including payment card PIN management, credit and debit card encryption and related technologies and processes.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The PCI Council has also stated support for tokenization in reducing risk in data breaches, when combined with other technologies such as Point-to-Point Encryption (P2PE) and assessments of compliance to PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Visa Inc. released Visa Tokenization Best Practices for tokenization uses in credit and debit card handling applications and services.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] In March 2014, EMVCo LLC released its first payment tokenization specification for EMV.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] PCI DSS is the most frequently utilized standard for Tokenization systems used by payment industry players.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Tokenization can render it more difficult for attackers to gain access to sensitive data outside of the tokenization system or service.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Implementation of tokenization may simplify the requirements of the PCI DSS, as systems that no longer store or process sensitive data may have a reduction of applicable controls required by the PCI DSS guidelines.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] This validation is particularly important in tokenization, as the tokens are shared externally in general use and thus exposed in high risk, low trust environments.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] The infeasibility of reversing a token or set of tokens to a live sensitive data must be established using industry accepted measurements and proofs by appropriate experts independent of the service or solution provider.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Not all organizational data can be tokenized, and needs to be examined and filtered.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] When databases are utilized on a large scale, they expand exponentially, causing the search process to take longer, restricting system performance, and increasing backup processes.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] A database that links sensitive information to tokens is called a vault.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] With the addition of new data, the vault's maintenance workload increases significantly.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] For ensuring database consistency, token databases need to be continuously synchronized.
[src:pci-dss/tokenization-data-security] Apart from that, secure communication channels must be built between sensitive data and the vault so that data is not compromised on the way to or from storage.
